Also, in the case of the WR model, it is possible to observe that the kinetic constant of the dissociation reaction (


                                 k


                                 r


                        ) does not present a meaningful impact on the conductivity either. Such observation ultimately suggests that despite the dissociation reaction indeed impacting the conductivity of the electrolyte, such effect is mostly given by its equilibrium conditions (i.e. influenced by the dissociation fraction at equilibrium, 
                           δ
                        ) than necessarily the dynamic behavior of such reaction — that is represented by the kinetic constant (


                                 k


                                 r


                        ).

Nonetheless, such neural networks still present a reliable alternative for conductivity estimation just by knowing the diffusion coefficients and the ion concentration — or, in case the chemical composition is known, the material density. In case the dissociation reaction is being taken into consideration, the dissociation fraction at equilibrium (
                           δ
                        ) is also necessary even though the kinetic constants are not relevant according to the results previously presented in Fig. 4.

To enable the estimation of conductivity for the selected materials, and in the absence of reported equilibrium ion concentration values (


         a


         0


), this parameter was approximated based on the material’s density and molar mass, with appropriate consideration of ionic stoichiometry. For simplicity, the equilibrium dissociation fraction (
   δ
) was assumed to be unity, and equal diffusion coefficients were considered for both positive and negative charge carriers. These approximations allowed for a practical evaluation of the performance of the proposed methods when applied to real materials. The corresponding results are presented in Table 10.
